    "breadcrumb": "Competency-Based Assessment",
    "content": "Competency assessment in this program operates at the program level, not the course level. Competencies belong to the degree, not to individual courses; courses are evidence-generating contexts. A student’s competency record is maintained across their entire time in the program through the Crystalis assessment platform.\nHow Evidence Accumulates Assessment is continuous and based on a preponderance of evidence — no single event determines a competency level. Evidence accumulates from multiple courses and multiple evidence types, and Crystalis aggregates it into a frequently-updated assessment score with a confidence interval visible to both faculty and the individual student, along with a reviewable record of contributing evidence, claims, assessments, and collected artifacts (such as the code that was assessed).\nEvidence Tiers Two evidence tiers feed the competency record:\nTier 1 — Automated Evidence\nCrystalis collects telemetry automatically from instrumented learning environments:\nE-textbook and video engagement Embedded H5P exercises (scaffolded code workouts and interactive worksheets) Git logs and commit history Time logs AI chat prompt and response logs Near real-time keystroke and event logging from instrumented IDEs Automatically collected evidence is aggregated into claims that faculty review and approve. Automated evidence can contribute up to the Application level.\nTier 2 — Direct Observable Assessments\nFaculty evaluate directly observable student work through LTI 3.0-integrated rubrics. These assessments are designed to expose student thinking and comprehension in contexts that automated evidence cannot capture:\nCode readings and code reviews Debugging challenges Design briefs and evaluation reports Performance assessments and reflection assessments Integrative projects Direct assessments can reach Independence, Adaptation, and Leadership.\nThe Competency Level Scale Level Description Exposure Recognizes concepts and vocabulary Application Uses the skill in structured tasks Independence Uses the skill without scaffolding Adaptation Applies the skill in novel contexts Leadership Teaches, critiques, and improves practice Leadership is not limited to course contexts. Students can demonstrate Leadership through undergraduate TA/LA roles, club leadership, peer mentoring, conference presentations, and other professional engagement outside the classroom.\nParallel Tracks: Grades and Competencies Grades live in administrative course containers and reflect a student’s learning engagement within that course — they are not solely a measure of proficiency. Competency levels live in the program-level Crystalis record and reflect demonstrated capability across multiple contexts.\nThese are parallel tracks, not redundant ones. A student may pass a course without yet demonstrating independence on a competency; a student may demonstrate a competency through non-course evidence before the relevant course has formally been completed.\nGraduation Artifacts Students graduate with two records:\nTraditional transcript — course-by-course grade record Final competency report — program-level competency assessment with evidence citations and a reviewable evidence trail Students may prepare an employer-facing version of their competency report through Crystalis: a curated presentation of their competency levels with selected supporting evidence artifacts (code samples, assessments, project work) chosen by the student.\nTarget Level The program’s aspiration is that every student exits at the Adaptation level or above across all competencies. Due to institutional constraints, competency levels are maintained as a parallel record independent of graduation requirements.",
    "description": "Competency assessment in this program operates at the program level, not the course level. Competencies belong to the degree, not to individual courses; courses are evidence-generating contexts. A student’s competency record is maintained across their entire time in the program through the Crystalis assessment platform.\nHow Evidence Accumulates Assessment is continuous and based on a preponderance of evidence — no single event determines a competency level. Evidence accumulates from multiple courses and multiple evidence types, and Crystalis aggregates it into a frequently-updated assessment score with a confidence interval visible to both faculty and the individual student, along with a reviewable record of contributing evidence, claims, assessments, and collected artifacts (such as the code that was assessed).",
