    "breadcrumb": "Competency-Based Assessment",
    "content": "Signature assessments are the five formal, high-stakes assessment events distributed across the program. Each is a culminating instance of a recurring assessment type — it represents that type at its most consequential, typically involving real artifacts, peer or faculty audience, and no scaffolding.\nCode Archaeology Milestone Block 2 — CS-105 Code Reading \u0026 Repair\nStudents investigate an unfamiliar, moderately complex codebase — written in languages they know — to explain its behavior, identify sources of unexpected behavior, and propose a repair. This is the first unscaffolded instance of the Code Archaeology recurring type.\nCode Archaeology does not end at Block 2. It recurs and deepens throughout the program (see Recurring Assessment Types), but the Block 2 milestone is the first formal, evaluated instance.\nEvidence generated: Analyze Computational Systems; Maintain Software Systems\nData Investigation Block 5 — CS-202 Database Design\nStudents identify a question they want to investigate, acquire or are given a novel dataset, and conduct a complete investigation: schema design, query strategy, statistical summarization, and interpretation. The investigation is documented and presented.\nThis is the formal instance of the Data Investigation recurring type and anchors the Store block’s evidence for the Data and Information domain.\nEvidence generated: Investigate Questions with Data; Manage Data Resources; Represent Information\nDesign Review Block 7 — CS-207 Graphs \u0026 Network Algorithms\nStudents present a system design — algorithm selection, data model choice, and architectural tradeoffs — to a panel of peers and faculty and defend their choices under critique. The defense must address correctness, performance, human-centered concerns, and ethical implications.\nDesign Review is the highest-stakes instance of both the Design Brief and the Technical Explanation Task recurring types. It recurs in a lighter form at Block 8.\nEvidence generated: Design Software Systems; Develop Abstractions; Evaluate Algorithmic Solutions; Communicate Technical Information; Evaluate Ethical Implications\nTeam Software Project Block 6 (CS-206) through Block 8 (CS-211)\nStudents collaborate on a shared software product across three blocks, taking it from requirements through implementation, testing, deployment, and a blameless postmortem. The project carries a responsibility retrospective at Block 6 and a final postmortem at Block 8.\nThis is the primary evidence context for the Professional Practice domain and generates sustained evidence for collaborative, implementation, maintenance, and verification competencies.\nEvidence generated: Collaborate on Software Teams; Implement Software Solutions; Verify Software Quality; Maintain Software Systems; Evaluate Ethical Implications; Reflect on Professional Growth\nSystem Integration Project Block 8 — CS-211 Human-Centered Design \u0026 Validation\nStudents design, build, deploy, and validate a multi-component system for real users. The project includes formal requirements gathering, acceptance testing with actual users, and a blameless postmortem. Students prepare an employer-facing competency report drawing on their full Crystalis evidence record.\nThis is the program’s culminating assessment event and generates evidence across all six competency domains.\nEvidence generated: All domains; final evidence anchor for Adaptation-level claims",
    "description": "Signature assessments are the five formal, high-stakes assessment events distributed across the program. Each is a culminating instance of a recurring assessment type — it represents that type at its most consequential, typically involving real artifacts, peer or faculty audience, and no scaffolding.\nCode Archaeology Milestone Block 2 — CS-105 Code Reading \u0026 Repair\nStudents investigate an unfamiliar, moderately complex codebase — written in languages they know — to explain its behavior, identify sources of unexpected behavior, and propose a repair. This is the first unscaffolded instance of the Code Archaeology recurring type.",
