    "content": "Working draft for faculty review. A bounded practice deepens only in student judgment while its scope deliberately stays flat — the single thread of this type, distinct from the nine spirals and three lenses.\nIn one line: Depth increases only in the student’s critical judgment; the SCOPE of permitted AI use stays narrow and constant — explain, discuss, quiz, critique — never “write this for me and I’ll submit it.”\nCharacter Structurally different from spirals and lenses by deliberate constraint. The Year 3–4 Agentic AI specialization depends on comprehension built here; if AI use grew more autonomous over the two years, it would become the crutch the foundation must avoid. So what grows is student judgment, not AI’s role. What is EXCLUDED — AI generating substantial code the student merely reviews and submits — should be named explicitly in every host syllabus.\nPasses across the two years Block Host context What’s escalating (scope stays constant) B1 (Y1 Fall) CS-101/102 / CS-105 AI as explainer for unfamiliar code; student verifies the explanation against actual behavior using the same block’s asserts/logs. B5 (Y2 Fall) CS-202 Database Design AI as a design-alternatives / tradeoff discussion partner; the final choice and justification are the student’s own. B6 (Y2 Fall) CS-206 Collaborative Development AI-assisted code review as ONE input among several — not a replacement for human review. B8 (Y2 Spring) CS-212 Data Analysis \u0026 Responsible AI High-stakes: given AI-GENERATED code, critique it for correctness and security. Prerequisite skill for the Year 3–4 specialization, which this precedes but does not duplicate. Connections B8 converges with Trustworthy Computing and Correctness \u0026 Verification (verifying AI output for safety and correctness). Open questions for faculty review Confirm the flat-scope boundary is right — conservative enough to protect comprehension, not so conservative it undersells what the specialization needs students to trust about AI tools. The exclusion (no AI writing substantial submitted code) should be stated in every host course’s syllabus. For how this lands in a specific block, see that block’s review file.",
    "description": "Working draft for faculty review. A bounded practice deepens only in student judgment while its scope deliberately stays flat — the single thread of this type, distinct from the nine spirals and three lenses.\nIn one line: Depth increases only in the student’s critical judgment; the SCOPE of permitted AI use stays narrow and constant — explain, discuss, quiz, critique — never “write this for me and I’ll submit it.”",
